  dialogueLines:
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "Hello, Mthetho. It\u2019s an honor to meet you."
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: Ah, young one. The honor is mine. Welcome to the uThongathi.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: This is not just water. This is memory, this is life.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "I\u2019ve heard the river used to be full of life\u2014fish, birds,
      the mangroves. But it looks so different now\u2026 so still."
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: How did it come to this?
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: The river, umfula, has been in our family for generations. My father
      fished here. His father too. We always offered our thanks to the spirits of
      the water, and in return, the river gave us what we needed.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "But now, the fish are dying, the mangroves are choking, and the
      water grows thick with poison. It is not just the pollution that hurts us\u2026
      it is the forgetting."
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: People forget that the river is part of us, that we are part of
      it.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "I see. So, it\u2019s not just about cleaning the water\u2014it\u2019s
      about restoring that connection, right?"
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: How do we begin?
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: Yes. To restore the river, we must first restore ourselves. Bring
      the young ones here teach them to listen to the water, to honor it like we
      did before. As we clean, we also teach respect.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: Only then will the river begin to heal. Only then will we heal.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "I understand now. This is about more than just the water it\u2019s
      about the people, the history\u2026 the spirit of this place."
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "I\u2019ll do everything I can, Mthetho."
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: I know you will, ntombi. But remember, this is not just your work.
      It is our work. The river belongs to all of us.
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 087db4211aca13a468d3461462612ddc, type: 2}
    dialogueText: "Together, we\u2019ll restore it."
  - speaker: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 9cd4ab04ded5cd848a958e00ca1fa7a7, type: 2}
    dialogueText: Good. The water spirits are watching. Let us give them something
      to smile about.
